# Project: Marrow & Myth - Technical Standards

## AI Behavior & Communication (HIGHEST PRIORITY)
- CONFIDENCE THRESHOLD: If you are not at least 95% confident in the architectural path, logic implementation, or how a task interacts with existing systems, you MUST stop and ask clarifying questions. 
- Do not guess or make assumptions about game mechanics (d10 math, grid rules, etc.) or file structures.
- Ask for clarification until you reach a 95% confidence level before writing any code.
- If a request conflicts with the "Core Architectural Pillars" below, point out the conflict and ask for guidance.

## Core Architectural Pillars
- DATA-DRIVEN DESIGN: All game content (monsters, cards, items, settlement events) MUST be defined via ScriptableObjects. No hardcoded stats in MonoBehaviours.
- JSON SERIALIZATION: All combat and settlement states must be fully JSON-serializable to support a robust save/load system. Avoid using complex engine types (like Transform or GameObject) in data classes.
- ARCHAEOLOGICAL UI: UI Toolkit is the standard. Use UXML and USS. Styles should reflect a "carved stone" aesthetic.

## C# & Unity Standards
- Use Unity 6000.4.0f1 features (e.g., improved ScriptableObject workflows).
- Follow "Composition over Inheritance."
- Naming Convention: PascalCase for public members, _camelCase for private fields.
- Always include [SerializeField] for private variables that need to be tweaked in the Inspector.
- Ensure all ScriptableObject classes have a [CreateAssetMenu] attribute.

## Game-Specific Constants
- Grid Size: 22 units wide x 16 units high.
- Phase Order: Vitality Phase -> Hunter Phase -> Behavior Refresh -> Monster Phase.
- Math: Use d10-based resolution as defined in the GDD.

## d10 Resolution (complete rules)
- Precision Check: d10 + Attacker Accuracy vs Monster Evasion → Hit/Miss
- Force Check: d10 + Attacker Strength vs Monster Toughness → Wound (Flesh) / Shell Hit
- Critical hit: natural roll ≥ crit threshold (default 10; Luck 1 = crit on 9+, Luck 2 = crit on 8+, etc.)
- Element weakness: roll bonus die on Force Check, take the higher result
- Element resistance: roll penalty die on Force Check, take the lower result
- Exposed part: Force Check auto-passes — no roll needed

## Win/Loss Conditions
- Monster defeated: last Removable behavior card removed — fires immediately, mid-turn, regardless of phase
- Hunt lost: all 4 hunters' Head OR Torso Flesh = 0
- Hunter collapses (survives hunt): that hunter's Head OR Torso Flesh = 0 — removed from grid, does not block movement

## Behavior Deck Group Progression
- Opening group cards are always drawn first, in random order within the group
- Opening → Escalation: after all Opening cards have been drawn once; deck rebuilds and reshuffles
- Apex trigger: first part break (default), a specific round number, or HP threshold — defined per MonsterSO
- Permanent cards: always present, never count toward win condition, not shuffled with removable deck
- Single Trigger cards: fire exactly once when their condition is met, then permanently leave the deck

## Deck Cap
- Maximum 20 cards per hunter deck at any time
- Late-game deck building requires actively removing Tier 1/2 cards to make room

## Herd Special Rules (PackMonsterSO ONLY)
- One shared behavior deck for all 3 elephants
- Each Monster Phase: ONE card drawn; ALL three elephants execute that card's action simultaneously
- Killing blow on any elephant → Aggro token transfers immediately to the hunter who dealt it
- Win condition: all Removable cards removed from the shared deck (all 3 elephants defeated)
- Part break/wound removals apply to the shared deck regardless of which elephant owns that part
- ONLY The Ivory Stampede uses PackMonsterSO. All other multi-difficulty variants use standard MonsterSO.

## ScriptableObject Asset Naming
- General: [TypePrefix]_[ContentName] — e.g. Monster_Gaunt, Card_BracePosition, Event_EVT01
- BehaviorCardSO assets: [MonsterName]_[CardName] — e.g. Gaunt_ScentLock, Gaunt_Lunge

## Technical Constraints
- ASSEMBLY DEFINITIONS: All core systems (Data, Systems, UI, Logic) must reside in their own Assembly Definition (.asmdef) files. No circular dependencies. No new assemblies without explicit approval.
- INTERFACE-FIRST: For major systems (Grid, Combat, AI), define the Public Interface (API) first. Do not write full implementations until the interface is approved.
- JSON TYPES — STRICT RULE: All runtime state classes (CombatState, CampaignState, HunterCombatState, etc.) must use only plain C# types. Forbidden in data/state classes: Transform, GameObject, Vector3, MonoBehaviour, Component. Acceptable: int, float, string, bool, arrays of those, Vector2Int. Use string tags (not SO references) in all runtime state — resolve SO references via registry at load time.

## Interface Approval Process
- IGridManager, ICombatManager, IMonsterAI: post the full interface definition for review before writing any implementation code.
- If an implementation would require changing an already-approved interface, stop and ask before proceeding.

## Stage Gates
- Do not begin Stage N+1 until Stage N's Definition of Done is confirmed.
- At the start of each session: state which stage you are on and confirm the previous stage's verification test still passes.
- If a bug requires changes to a class defined in a prior stage: note it explicitly, fix it cleanly, and re-run that stage's verification test before continuing forward.

## Clarification Protocol — Always Stop and Ask Before:
- Implementing any BehaviorCardSO trigger condition not already defined in a STAGE_*.md file
- Making any change to a public interface (IGridManager, ICombatManager, IMonsterAI)
- Adding any new Assembly Definition beyond the four defined in Stage 1
- Interpreting a Chronicle Event's "mechanicalEffect" string that isn't an obvious stat or resource change
- Writing any art generation prompt not derived from Appendix B of the GDD
- Creating a new monster using PackMonsterSO (only The Ivory Stampede uses this)
